text: The Rambo of the 'First Blood' film disliked violence (including using it himself) and war increasingly as the movie progressed. Then the studio and/or others involved in making the Rambo franchise realized that if they put more explosions and loud "BOOM!" in their movies, they could draw in a large audience repeatedly even if the plot, character development, and/or other elements of the movies lacked in some way. Considering that John Rambo is a fairly old man in the upcoming 'Last Blood' story, I had hoped that maybe his character would perhaps become a little more self-reflective and go back to showing at least some signs of his old dislike (if not downright despising) of using violence as a means to reach his goals. Alas, I see no hint of that in this trailer and quite the opposite, really; he seems to know that others are bad for violently killing people Rambo loves, but then he seems to be committed to escalating things further in response, an action that the Rambo of 'First Blood' would doubtlessly not condone.

text: I saw Rambo: First Blood back in the mid-80's and the sequels during the late 80's - I was way too young, but I'm so glad I met my hero John J. back then, I've been an ardent fan of Stallone and his movies ever since. I played the video games with Commodore 64, I bought the Rambo knife, I even got a bow and three arrows and went shooting on the football field...until I had to take a break and cycle to the nearest supermarket to buy some soda with my pocket change! Oh, good memories from 30 years past...  The magic and magnetism of the classic Rambo movies has not faded away throughout the decades. I just watched First Blood again and enjoyed it thoroughly - true classics never lose their sparkle!  Rambo never wants war, he just wants peace and quiet...but when the forces of tyranny make him take a stand, he will fight it until he destroys the enemy. So there's a sense of admirable justice in these films. I know it's brutal war and I don't want war anywhere or for anyone, but the idea of defeating the outnumbering enemy for the sake of justice is truly something to admire.  Me and my friend truly enjoyed Rambo (IV) as we went to see it in the cinema. The movie was a successful continuum in Rambo's tale, a fitting battle against another tyrannical adversary.  Now this Last Blood will be one of the most anticipated movies in Stallone's canon, I really can't wait to see this!

text: I feel that everyone deserves to either love or hate this movie. I personally loved it, and I did a little rambo research and binge watching after seeing it so I could have a real opinion, I feel it was well written and VERY well acted, because the director had more emotional and humanizing moments for John Rambo than in some of the other movies, and for a movie titled "last blood" I feel these moments are fitting because this is his last time acting as the legend he was, modern day critics expect female power and "oh make everything happy and equal" when that isn't reality, this movie is incredibly realistic, John Rambo is a smart military man who is after revenge for his step-daughter. Why is it realistic? because if someone drugged me to the point of death and the men who did it were after my MOM, she would do the same fucking thing, cause SHE is a smart military woman who fought in a war, she fought in Iraq, and trust me she has been in combat, and if she can take down her own son who was an inch taller than her, and with a bad back, shoulder, knees, and messed up head from all the explosions shaking her brain around?  No doubt in my mind she could do what he did, possibly more since she was in the army for 20 YEARS. What I'm trying to say here is that this is a realistic, emotional, and epic finale to a great movie series that many people sadly don't understand because they want either all action and no story or woman power and equal representation.
